# Task 8 Revival

This folder contains the Arduino sketch for Task 8: Touch-Based Robot Revival.

The aim of this task is for the active robot to approach a stationary stranded robot, slow down as it gets closer, and make mechanical contact using the bumper switch within 60 seconds.

## Folder Structure

```text
task8_revival/
  task8_revival.ino
  README.md
```

## Task 8: Touch-Based Robot Revival

File:

```text
task8_revival/task8_revival.ino
```

Scenario:

The robot is given the position of a stationary stranded robot. It needs to drive towards it in a controlled way and make contact using the bumper switch.

Strategy:

```text
start the revival attempt
-> read the front distance sensor
-> calculate the distance error
-> use a P controller to set the approach speed
-> slow down as the robot gets closer
-> keep moving until the bumper switch is pressed
-> stop the motors
-> turn the green LED on
```

## Sensors and Outputs Used

```text
Front UART distance sensor: measures distance to the target robot
Bumper switch: confirms mechanical contact
Motoron motor controller: drives the left and right motors
Red LED: shows the task is still running or has failed
Green LED: shows successful bumper contact
Serial Monitor: prints distance, speed, bumper status, and state
```

## Main Controller

```text
P controller for approach speed + bumper switch contact detection
```

## Main States

```text
APPROACHING_TARGET
REVIVAL_DONE
RESCUE_FAILED
```

## Important Parameters

```cpp
const unsigned long rescueTimeLimit = 60000;

const uint32_t targetDistanceMm = 140;
const int minDriveSpeed = 120;
const int maxDriveSpeed = 350;
const float distanceGain = 0.45;
```

## How the Approach Works

The robot uses the front distance sensor to measure how far it is from the stranded robot.

The distance error is calculated using:

```cpp
distanceError = distanceMm - targetDistanceMm;
```

The approach speed is calculated using:

```cpp
speed = minDriveSpeed + (distanceGain * distanceError);
```

This means:

```text
large distance error
-> robot is far away
-> drive speed is higher

small distance error
-> robot is close to the target
-> drive speed is lower

bumper switch pressed
-> contact made
-> stop the robot
-> turn green LED on
```

The speed is limited between `minDriveSpeed` and `maxDriveSpeed` so the robot does not stall at low speed or approach too aggressively at high speed.

## Why We Used a P Controller

A P controller is used because the robot only needs to reduce its speed as it gets closer to the target. It does not need to hold an exact distance from the stranded robot.

The bumper switch gives the final confirmation of contact, so the distance sensor is only used to control the approach speed before contact.

A full PID controller was not used because the integral term could build up too much error while the robot is far away, which may cause a harder impact near the target. The derivative term could also react to noisy distance sensor readings and make the movement jerky.

For this task, a P controller is simpler, easier to tune, and works well for controlled deceleration.

## Contact Detection

The bumper switch is connected using `INPUT_PULLUP`.

This means:

```text
LOW  = bumper pressed
HIGH = bumper not pressed
```

As soon as the bumper switch is pressed, the robot stops and the revival is marked as complete.

The code does not wait for a fixed contact time because the task only requires successful mechanical contact.

## LED Behaviour

```text
Red LED on:
  revival is still in progress or the robot failed to make contact in time

Green LED on:
  bumper contact has been made and revival is complete
```

## Tuning Values

The main values to tune are:

```cpp
const uint32_t targetDistanceMm = 140;
const int minDriveSpeed = 120;
const int maxDriveSpeed = 350;
const float distanceGain = 0.45;
```

### `targetDistanceMm`

This is the distance where the robot should already be moving slowly.

Increase it if the robot slows down too late or hits the target too hard.

Decrease it if the robot slows down too early and takes too long to reach the bumper.

### `minDriveSpeed`

This is the slowest speed the robot will use.

Increase it if the robot gets close to the target but does not have enough power to press the bumper.

Decrease it if the robot is still moving too quickly near the target.

### `maxDriveSpeed`

This is the fastest speed the robot is allowed to use.

Increase it if the robot is too slow from far away.

Decrease it if the robot approaches too aggressively.

### `distanceGain`

This is the proportional gain, also known as the Kp value.

Increase it if the robot needs to respond more strongly to distance changes.

Decrease it if the robot approaches too fast or the movement is not smooth enough.

## Testing Order

```text
1. Check that the bumper switch reads correctly in the Serial Monitor.
2. Check that the front distance sensor gives sensible distance readings.
3. Test the motors at a low speed to confirm the forward direction.
4. Test the robot from a short distance first.
5. Tune minDriveSpeed so the robot can still move slowly near the target.
6. Tune maxDriveSpeed so the robot does not approach too aggressively.
7. Tune distanceGain until the approach feels smooth.
8. Test from the expected starting distance and check that contact happens within 60 seconds.
```

## Expected Behaviour

```text
red LED turns on
-> robot starts approaching the stranded robot
-> speed reduces as the robot gets closer
-> bumper switch is pressed
-> robot stops
-> green LED turns on
-> revival is complete
```

If contact is not made within 60 seconds:

```text
robot stops
-> red LED stays on
-> Serial Monitor prints that the revival attempt failed
```

## Notes

The sketch is currently written as a standalone test for Task 8.

Negative motor speed is used as forward movement for this robot setup.

The right motor direction is reversed in the code because of how the motors are mounted.

Only the front distance sensor is used for the approach speed. The other UART sensor readings are still read and stored, but they are not used in the main revival logic yet.

The Serial Monitor prints useful debugging information once per second, including the current state, front distance, drive speed, bumper status, and elapsed time.
